eThekwini remains KwaZulu-Natal’s epicenter with the highest infections and COVID-19 deaths and it doesn’t look like the province’s economic hub will be moving to level four of the lockdown anytime soon. eThekwini registers new cases almost daily. Courtesy #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - KwaZulu Natal Premier Sihle Zikalala is worried about relaxing lockdown regulations as the number of infections and deaths in eThekwini rise. The district is likely to remain on level 5 lockdown. While most of South Africa will be entering level 4 of the lockdown on 1 May, the eThekwini district is likely to remain under stricter regulations. At least 29 people have died of COVID-19 in the province, of which 25 are in eThekwini. READ: Cele apologises for comments made during arrest at Mpumalanga mosque The district also has 579 confirmed cases. Coronavirus Hotline Number: 0800 029 999 from 8am to 4pm, Monday to Friday Help protect your loved ones by sharing this official South African government COVID-19 service with your family, friends and community. Send HI to 0600 123 456 on WhatsApp. The NICD has another Clinician Hotline to improve #COVID19 communication and support for healthcare providers. The Clinician Hotline is 0800 11 1131, operating 24 hrs. The Public Hotline is 0800 029 999 also operating 24hrs. KwaZulu-Natal Premier Sihle Zikalala will update the media on what the relaxation of the lockdown means for the province as well as other issues on the Covid-19 epidemic.